How does he just casually kill soldier of godrick, he is literally the strongest boss ever
for those who are new and dont understand the flasks. The Red flasks are for healing (red bar), the blue flasks are for magic (blue bar), and the third flask is one you can create by using tears that can give you more strength, health, and/or stamina and/or magic. you can pick up the tears throught the wold of elden ring and can use up to 2 tears and can only use it once, and to refill your 3 flasks you must rest at a grace site the same as reviving enemies but bosses (the enemies that have the longer red bar on the bottom of your screen. Now for runes. if youre familiar with dark souls then you should also know elden ring is a souls game but instead of getting souls from enemies you unalive you receive runes. they work the same, you use those runes to level up and buy equipment, upgrade spirit summons, and upgrade equipment. and if you die your runes are lost but you can get them back but if you die again and dont recover your runes you previously lost they banish no way to recive and you have to restart getting runes from 0.

About your elgato problem, it's hard to know for sure how to pin down any potential problems without knowing your setup: specs, settings ect. But with a blind guess I'd say  A: lower the resolution you record in Or B: do a dual pc set up (if you're not already doing so)  I use elgato as well and record for 1-3 hours at a time and had a similar issue at first. The encoder on the elgato can possibly strain your graphics card. Leading to visual and audio errors.  Again it's hard to tell for sure without working on it myself or getting a play by play feedback directly from you. So with this little bit of info I hope it helps. If not feel free to contact me and I'll help as best as I can. Or find some helpful videos to send your way. Anyway, Great videos keep it up! You're still the goat! â˜ºï¸  Edit: I did some research and replicated the problem on my setup. I assume you're using the elgato game capture app. If so. STOP! it tends to desync your audio. Use OBS capture from there using the elgato chat-link. Make sure it's set to analog audio in elgato game capture app, close it and then set OBS audio to analog as well. Problem should be fixed

LETS GOOOO
Cory, about your elgato capture card. So I have this same problem with recording. I don't think you can fix the card from it's "problem" but you can work with it. I think your problem is that your card and your microphone are recording at different rates if that makes sense. So over time they will gradually de-sync. You can fix this in editing if you just change your capture card to record in drop frames and have you mic record in the corresponding Hz. If you want your videos to be at 60fps (which I assume you do, because I would too.) you need to set your capture card to record at 59.94 frames a second and have a 48Hz microphone capture rate accompanying with it. If you want to record at 30fps, you need to set the capture card to 29.997 and have the same 48Hz recording rate. Basically what happens is if you're recording at true 60p (60fps) or true 30p or any true even number fps, every frame video (so 1/60th of a second for 60fps) your microphone is going to have a little bit less audio recording available for that frame (so the frame is longer than the audio that's playing with it). so after 60 frames (one second), you now have your audio off by 1/60 of a second. and after a minute your audio is off by a whole second and etc. etc. This doesn't really become noticeable until after half an hour, which is exactly when you said you started noticing when you audio is off! Which is why I believe this is the problem you're having. Let me know if you want to contact me so I can help walk you through how to fix this.
